'''''The Magic School Bus''''' is an [[Television in the United States|American]] [[Educational entertainment|edutainment]] [[media franchise]] that consists of [[The Magic School Bus (book series)|a book series]], [[The Magic School Bus (TV series)|a TV series]], and [[The Magic School Bus (video games)|several video games]], among other things. Each of the stories within the franchise centers on the antics of a fictional [[elementary school]] [[teacher]], Ms. Frizzle, and her class, who board a "magic [[school bus]]", which takes them on field trips to unusual locations, such as the solar system, clouds, the [[Time travel|past]], and inside the human body.

== History ==
The first media in which this franchise was developed was [[The Magic School Bus (book series)|the ''Magic School Bus'' book series]]. Craig Walker, vice-president and senior editorial director at Scholastic Co., stated that the concept began with the idea of combining science with fictional stories, and [[Joanna Cole (author)|Joanna Cole]] (who had written both science and humor before) and [[Bruce Degen]] were then approached with creating such a series. Walker also states that his own memories of school field trips and of a teacher he had once, served as further inspiration.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-book-news/article/2947-two-decades-of-fun-and-learning-on-the-magic-school-bus.html |title=Two Decades of Fun and Learning on the Magic School Bus |accessdate=2012-10-03 |last=Lodge |first=Sally |date=2006-07-27 |work=Publisher’s Weekly }}</ref> The first book "At the Waterworks" was written in 1985 and published the following year. The books are written in the [[first-person narrative|first person]] from the point of view of an unnamed student in "the Friz's" class. Cole and Degen started a new series called ''Ms. Frizzle's Adventures'' in 2001, which teaches [[social studies]], eventually producing three books in that series. [[Microsoft Home]] started publishing ''Magic School Bus'' software in 1994.

In 1994, ''The Magic School Bus'' concept was also made into [[The Magic School Bus (TV series)|an animated series of the same name]] by [[Scholastic Entertainment]], and premiered on September 10, 1994. Scholastic Entertainment president Deborah Forte says that adapting the books into an animated series was an opportunity to help kids "learn about science in a fun way".<ref name="Clarke">{{cite journal |last=Clarke |first=Melanie M. |date=2005-06-20 |title=A Scholastic Achievement |journal=Broadcasting & Cable |volume=135 |issue=25 |pages=30 |publisher=Cahners Publishing Co./Reed Publishing (USA) Inc. |location= |issn= }}</ref> Around that time, Forte had been hearing concern from parents and teachers about how to improve science education for girls and minorities.<ref name="Clarke"/> As noted by Marcel LaFollette, "accomplished women were exceptions in a universe of male luminaries" when it came to science television.<ref name=LaFollette2013/>{{rp|185}} Miss Valerie Frizzle, the magic school teacher, was the closest approximation to an expert female host.<ref name=Halpern>{{cite journal|last1=Halpern|first1=Paul|title=On the Air|journal=Distillations|publisher=Chemical Heritage Foundation | date=2015|volume=1|issue=2|page=44|url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/magazine/on-the-air|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=LaFollette2013>{{cite book|last1=LaFollette|first1=Marcel Chotkowski|title=Science on American television : a history|date=2013|publisher=University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago, Ill.|chapter=Rarae Aves: Television's Female Scientists|pp=185-195|isbn=978-0-226-92199-0}}</ref>{{rp|183, 185–195}} She was voiced by [[Lily Tomlin]] in the series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0005499/|title=Lily Tomlin|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-04-25}}</ref> 

Each episode of the series ran for 30 minutes. In the United States, the series originally aired on [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] as a part of its children's block, PTV (later renamed [[PBS Kids]]), through [[South Carolina]]'s [[South Carolina Educational Television|SCETV]] network; it was the first fully animated series to be aired on PBS. The last episode aired on December 6, 1997; the series then aired reruns on PBS until September 1998. The [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] network aired repeats from September 1998 to September 2002. Starting September 27, 2010, ''The Magic School Bus'' started a daily run on [[Qubo]] in the US, and on Saturday mornings on [[NBC]] through June 30th, 2012, when the [[Qubo]] block was replaced with the [[NBC Kids]] block.

From 1994 to 2000, several [[The Magic School Bus (video games)|''Magic School Bus'' video games]] were released. Most of the original titles were created by the software company [[Music Pen]] in collaboration with [[Microsoft]] and [[Scholastic Press]], the publisher of the ''Magic School Bus'' book series. Though in the cartoon series, the bus was obviously animated in the usual way, in the [[CD-ROM]] games, it is typically animated with [[computer generated imagery]]. In all these titles the user gets to "drive" the bus, which almost always involves clicking on the [[steering wheel]] and choosing a location. (The exception is ''The Magic School Bus Explores Inside the Earth'' where it is the gear shift instead of the steering wheel.) Most of the games have about seven different locations, including the classroom. There is always some goal for the user in each one.

[[Scholastic Entertainment]], the [[American Meteorological Society]] and the [[Children's Museum of Houston]] created a ''Scholastics the Magic School Bus Kicks Up a Storm'', a {{convert|2600|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}. traveling exhibit funded in part by the [[National Science Foundation]], which premiered at the Children's Museum of Houston in 2003 (a copy of it opened in [[New Jersey]] the month after that).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ams.confex.com/ams/84Annual/techprogram/paper_66953.htm |title=Scholastics the Magic School Bus Kicks Up a Storm Museum Exhibit |accessdate=2009-03-23 |last=McCallum |first=Cheryl D. |author2= L. Nazarani |author3=The Children's Museum of Houston |date=2007-01-04 |work=ams.confex.com |publisher=American Meteorological Society }}</ref>

On September 29, 2017, Scholastic and [[Netflix]] released the reboot animated series ''[[The Magic School Bus Rides Again]]'', with [[Kate McKinnon]] as the voice of Ms. Frizzle's sister, Fiona Felicity Frizzle, who is now in charge of the class. [[Lily Tomlin]] also reprises her role as Ms. Frizzle, now Professor Frizzle, Ph.D.

